                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-400-off2058 t18310908-400-crimeloc2061"></join>. I gave my watch to Mr. Madley, the landlord of the house, where I lodge; I afterwards traced it to Mr. Sheppard's - the prisoner lodged in the same house with me.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-400-person2858">
                  THOMAS 
                  MADLEY
               <interp inst="t18310908-400-person2858" type="surname" value="MADLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-400-person2858" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-400-person2858" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prosecutor gave me the watch; I put it into the bar - I locked it up at night, and my wife unlocked the bar; the next morning, when I came down, the watch was gone.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CLARKSON. Q.When did you lock it up? A. On Friday night, the 12th - the bar was found safe in the morning - the watch was not missed till the prosecutor came for it - the prisoner had been there, and appeared drunk.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-400-person2859">
                  JOSEPH 
                  SHEPPARD
               <interp inst="t18310908-400-person2859" type="surname" value="SHEPPARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-400-person2859" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-400-person2859" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a publican at Hammersmith. On Saturday morning, the 13th, the prisoner came to my house, he had some drink, and offered this watch for sale for 25s; I bought it of him for 1l.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. How much did you require him to spend in drink? A. They had 15s. worth - there were twelve or fifteen people in the tap-room; my house is the sign of the Friend at Hand - the prisoner was not drunk in my house.(Property produced, and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>The prisoner put in a written Defence, Stating that he had purchased the watch of a man whom he formerly lodged with.</p>
               <p>
